d:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["For years, the gaming PC market has been a battleground of extremes: either you overpay for a prebuilt with bloated margins, or you dive into the DIY rabbit hole, hunting for GPUs at scalper-inflated prices and praying your PSU doesn’t fry your motherboard. Best Buy’s latest deal—a ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.bestbuy.com","children":"CyberpowerPC rig"}]," packing an ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.amd.com/en/products/cpu/amd-ryzen-7-7800x3d","children":"AMD Ryzen 7 7800X3D"}]," and a ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.amd.com/en/products/graphics/amd-radeon-rx-7900xt","children":"Radeon RX 7900 XT"}]," (likely a typo in the original snippet, as the ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.techpowerup.com/gpu-specs/amd-radeon-rx-7900-xt.c4068","children":"RX 7900 XT"}]," is the current-gen flagship, not a mythical ‘9070 XT’) for ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"$$1,750"}],"—isn’t just another flash sale. It’s a rare moment where the math ",["$","em",null,{"children":"almost"}]," works in the consumer’s favor. And that’s worth dissecting.\nThe 7800X3D remains the ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.gamersnexus.net/hwreviews/4067-amd-ryzen-7-7800x3d-cpu-review-benchmarks-vs-intel-13900k","children":"undisputed 1080p gaming CPU"}]," for frame-chasing purists, while the RX 7900 XT, though overshadowed by Nvidia’s DLSS ecosystem, still delivers ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.techspot.com/review/2570-amd-radeon-rx-7900-xt/","children":"rationally competitive rasterization performance"}]," at 1440p and 4K. The kicker? Building this yourself right now would cost ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"~$1,800–$2,000"}],"—assuming you snag parts at MSRP, avoid the ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.3dcenter.org/news/amd-radeon-rx-7900-xt-und-rx-7900-xtx-im-preisverfall","children":"GPU markup rollercoaster"}],", and don’t factor in the value of your time (or the existential dread of troubleshooting a DOA motherboard). For a prebuilt, $1,750 isn’t just fair; it’s a ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"market correction"}],"—one that exposes how inflated ‘gaming rig’ pricing has become.\nBut here’s the catch: this deal isn’t for the hardcore DIY crowd. It’s for the ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"pragmatic majority"}],"—players who want a no-fuss, warranty-backed system that won’t require a PhD in BIOS settings to run ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Starfield"}]," without melting. CyberpowerPC’s reputation for ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.reddit.com/r/buildapc/comments/12x5z8j/cyberpowerpc_cable_management_is_a_crime/","children":"questionable cable management"}]," and ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://forums.tomshardware.com/threads/cyberpowerpc-reviews-good-or-bad.3765230/","children":"hit-or-miss QA"}]," lingers, but at this price, the trade-offs shift. The real question isn’t whether this is a ‘good deal’ (it is), but whether it signals a ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"permanent recalibration"}]," of what gamers should expect—or if it’s just Best Buy clearing inventory before ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.videocardz.com/newz/amd-radeon-rx-7800-xt-rx-7700-xt-rx-7600-launch-dates-leaked","children":"AMD’s next-gen GPUs"}]," land later this year."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/best-buys-1-750-ryzen-x3d-pc-deal-is-a-reality-che/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Kada je ‘dobar deal’ zapravo test tržišta—i tko ga stvarno treba?","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],"$L15"]}],"\n","$L16"]}]
